Ensuring an accurate base model is a prerequisite for achieving accurate predictions in the target domain. In this context, the performance of the LSTM model for the base PV is evaluated with the following procedure: The base PV dataset is split into train set and evaluation set using a 80-20 split, keeping the first 80% as training and the remaining 20% as testing (17563 observations for the training process and 4391 observations for evaluation purposes) and the LSTM model is trained on the training set. The accuracy of the model is evaluated by computing the root mean squared error (RMSE) and the mean absolute error (MAE) of the respective forecasts across the evaluation period considered, as well as the coefficient of determination R2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R^2$$\end{document} between the forecasts and the real values, as follows:7RMSE=1n∑t=1n(yt-yt^)2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
